  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in virtually every country around the world. They are a crucial part of the global effort to combat financial crime, including terrorism financing, drug trafficking, and corruption.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n*   **International Standards:** The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards for AML. Most countries adhere to these standards.\n*   **National Laws:** Each country implements AML regulations through its own laws. These laws typically include:\n\n    *   **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):** Requires financial institutions and other businesses to identify and verify the identity of their customers.\n    *   **Record Keeping:** Requires businesses to maintain records of transactions for a certain period.\n    *   **Reporting Suspicious Activity (SARs):** Requires businesses to report transactions that appear suspicious or that may involve money laundering or terrorist financing.\n    *   **Compliance Programs:** Requires businesses to establish and maintain internal AML compliance programs.\n\n*   **Enforcement:** Governments have agencies responsible for enforcing AML regulations. These agencies investigate and prosecute money laundering offenses.\n\nIn short, AML regulations are a widespread and essential part of the global legal landscape.",
